   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "23bb1030-4a9a-4605-93ce-870d11de7325",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sorting Sequences - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "31607fce-2cc7-4b20-b6ff-de3b1e381f95",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sorting and Sort Keys\n",
    "\n",
    "Sorting a sequence of numbers is something easily understood\n",
    "But we do have to consider the direction of the sort: ascending, descending\n",
    "\n",
    "Python provides sorted() function that will sort a given iterable\n",
    "Default sort direction is ascending\n",
    "\n",
    "The sorting() function has optional kwarg called reverse which defaults to False\n",
    "If we set it to True, then sort will sort in descending order\n",
    "\n",
    "But one important thing we need to think about is ordering. \n",
    "Only obvious with real numbers"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0f5b5f41-05f0-44f6-9577-f2f53458b884",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sorting and Sort Keys\n",
    "\n",
    "What about non-numerical values?\n",
    "'a', 'b', 'c'\n",
    "'A', 'a', 'B', 'b', 'C', 'c'\n",
    "'hello', 'python', 'bird', 'parrot'\n",
    "\n",
    "Strings are comparable so these are still okay, although is capital and lowercase considered?\n",
    "Lowercase is larger than uppercase\n",
    "\n",
    "(0, 0) (1, 1) (2, 2)\n",
    "(0, 0) (0, 1) (1, 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "rectangle_1, rectangle_2, rectangle_3\n",
    "\n",
    "When items are pairwise comparable (< or >) we can use that sort.\n",
    "But what happens when they aren't? -> Sort Keys\n",
    "\n",
    "'b', 'x', 'a' \n",
    "ASCII character codes (a -> 97, b -> 98, x -> 120); ord('a') -> 97\n",
    "We now associate ASCII numerical value with each character and sort based on value\n",
    "\n",
    "items/keys\n",
    "'b'/98, 'x'/120, 'a'/97 -> 'a'/97, 'b'/98, 'x'/120\n",
    "'B', 'b', 'A', 'a', 'X', 'x', '1', '?'\n",
    " 66   98   65   97   88  120   49  63\n",
    "\n",
    "-> '1', '?', 'A', 'B', 'X', 'a', 'b', 'x'\n",
    "You'll note that sort keys have a natural sort order"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "79276566-c2b0-4fcd-b535-d2f86f4d3513",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sorting and Sort Keys\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's say we want to sort a list of Person objects based on their age (assumes Person has age property)\n",
    "\n",
    "p1.age -> 30\n",
    "p2.age -> 15\n",
    "p3.age -> 5\n",
    "p4.age -> 32\n",
    "\n",
    "item/keys\n",
    "p1/30, p2/15, p3/5, p4/32 -> p3/5, p2/15, p1/30, p4/32\n",
    "\n",
    "We could also generate key value for any given person using a function\n",
    "\n",
    "def key(p):\n",
    "    return p.age\n",
    "\n",
    "key = lambda p: p.age\n",
    "\n",
    "sort[p1, p2, p3, p4]\n",
    "using sort keys generated by function key = lambda p: p.age\n",
    "\n",
    "The sort keys need not be numerical, they just need to have a natural sort order (< or >)\n",
    "item 'hello' 'python' 'parrot' 'bird'\n",
    "keys 'o' 'n' 't' 'd' \n",
    "(last character of each string)\n",
    "-> 'bird' 'python' 'hello' 'parrot'\n",
    "key = lambda s: s[-1]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f5d52c97-e3d7-47f3-a87a-ddaca5afb036",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Python's sorted function\n",
    "\n",
    "That's exactly what Python's sorted function allows us to do\n",
    "Optional keyword-only argument called key\n",
    "If provided, key must be a function that for any given element in sequence being sorted returns a key\n",
    "The sort key does not need to have numerical -> just needs to be values that are pairwise comparable (< >)\n",
    "If key is not provided, the Pythoin will sort based on natural ordering of elements (< >)\n",
    "If elements not pairwise comparable, you get an exception\n",
    "\n",
    "sorted(iterable, key=None, reverse=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "The sorted function:\n",
    "- makes a copy of the iterable\n",
    "- returns the sorted elements in a list\n",
    "- uses a sort algorithm called TimSort -> named after Tim Peters, Python 2.3, 2002\n",
    "- a stable sort\n",
    "\n",
    "Side note: for natural sort of elements we can think of keys as elements themselves\n",
    "\n",
    "sorted(iterable) <--> sorted(iterable, key=lambda x: x)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "baea0ebb-b04a-4604-a194-dca632b69568",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Stable Sorts\n",
    "\n",
    "A stable sort is one that maintains relative order of items that have equal keys (or values of natural ordering)\n",
    "\n",
    "p1.age -> 30\n",
    "p2.age -> 15\n",
    "p3.age -> 5\n",
    "p4.age -> 32\n",
    "p5.age -> 15\n",
    "\n",
    "sorted((p1, p2, p3, p4, p5), key=lambda p: p.age)\n",
    "\n",
    "[p3, p2, p5, p1, p4]\n",
    "\n",
    "keys equal, p2 preceded p5 in original tuple -> p2 precedes p5 in sorted list (note sets may be unordered)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "11e3a04d-78cf-4934-9a8f-baf295b73662",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In-Place Sorting\n",
    "\n",
    "If iterable is mutable, in-place sorting is possible\n",
    "But that will depend on particular type you are dealing with.\n",
    "Python's list objects support in-place sorting\n",
    "\n",
    "The list class has a sort() instance method that does in-place sorting.\n",
    "\n",
    "l = [10, 5, 3, 2]\n",
    "id(l) -> 0xFF42\n",
    "l.sort()\n",
    "l -> [2, 3, 5, 10]\n",
    "id(l) -> 0xFF42\n",
    "\n",
    "Compared to sorted()\n",
    "- same TimSort algorithm\n",
    "- same kwarg: key\n",
    "- same kwarg: reverse (default is False)"
   ]
  },
